---
// src/components/sections/FAQ.astro
const faqs = [
  { 
    q: "How long should a journal entry be?", 
    a: "As long as it needs to be. There is no minimum or maximum. Some of the most powerful entries are three sentences. Some are ten pages. The question is not length but honesty. A short, truthful entry will always produce more insight than a long, performative one. Start with whatever comes naturally and let length take care of itself." 
  },
  { 
    q: "Do I have to write every day to get the benefits?", 
    a: "No. Research shows that consistency over time matters more than daily frequency. Studies on expressive writing found significant benefits from writing just three to four times per week. What matters is that you write regularly enough to build a reflective habit — not that you never miss a day." 
  },
  { 
    q: "What if I don't know what to write?", 
    a: "Use a prompt. Start with one of the questions from the prompts section of this guide. Or simply write: 'Right now I don’t know what to write, and the reason is probably...' and let whatever follows surprise you. The blank page is a starting point, not a wall." 
  },
  { 
    q: "Is digital journaling as effective as paper journaling?", 
    a: "Research shows that handwriting may have a slight edge for emotional processing and memory retention due to the different neural pathways it engages. But digital journaling is far more effective than not journaling at all. Choose the format you will actually use consistently. Consistency always beats format." 
  },
  { 
    q: "Should I reread old journal entries?", 
    a: "Yes, periodically. Rereading old entries can reveal patterns, show you how far you have come, and surface recurring themes or beliefs that are worth examining. Many people find that rereading entries from a year ago provides a perspective on their own growth that nothing else can. For Morning Pages specifically, many practitioners recommend not rereading until you have accumulated several weeks of entries." 
  },
  { 
    q: "Can journaling replace therapy?", 
    a: "No — and it should not try to. Journaling is a powerful complement to therapy and a valuable standalone practice for general mental health and self-development. But for serious mental health conditions, trauma, or crisis, professional support is not replaceable. Think of journaling as something you can do between therapy sessions, or as a daily mental health practice that works alongside professional care rather than instead of it." 
  },
  { 
    q: "Which journaling technique is best for beginners?", 
    a: "Gratitude journaling is the most research-backed starting point for beginners because it is simple, takes less than five minutes, produces immediate positive effects, and builds a foundation of positive emotional awareness that makes other journaling techniques easier to sustain. Start there, do it consistently for 30 days, and then explore other journaling techniques once the habit is established." 
  }
];
---
<section class="py-10 px-4 md:px-6 max-w-4xl mx-auto">
  <div class="text-center mb-16">
    <span class="text-indigo-600 text-[10px] font-black tracking-[0.2em] uppercase mb-4 block">Knowledge Base</span>
    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-4xl font-black text-slate-900 tracking-tight leading-tight">
      Frequently Asked Questions <br class="hidden md:block" /> About Journaling
    </h2>
  </div>

  <div class="space-y-4">
    {faqs.map(faq => (
      <details class="group bg-white border border-slate-100 rounded-[32px] p-2 transition-all duration-500 hover:border-indigo-100 hover:shadow-xl hover:shadow-indigo-500/5 [&_summary::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
        
        <summary class="flex justify-between items-center cursor-pointer p-6 list-none outline-none">
          <span class="font-bold text-slate-800 text-base md:text-lg transition-colors group-hover:text-indigo-600 group-open:text-indigo-600 leading-snug pr-4">
            {faq.q}
          </span>
          
          <div class="relative flex-shrink-0 flex items-center justify-center w-10 h-10 rounded-full bg-slate-50 group-hover:bg-indigo-50 group-open:bg-indigo-600 transition-all duration-500">
             <span class="absolute w-3 h-0.5 bg-slate-400 group-open:bg-white transition-all duration-500"></span>
             <span class="absolute w-0.5 h-3 bg-slate-400 group-open:bg-white group-open:rotate-90 transition-all duration-500"></span>
          </div>
        </summary>

        <div class="px-6 pb-8 pt-2 overflow-hidden">
          <div class="text-slate-500 text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed border-t border-slate-50 pt-8 animate-fadeIn font-medium">
            {faq.a}
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>
    ))}
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  /* Smooth open animation */
  details[open] .animate-fadeIn {
    animation: fadeIn 0.6s cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1);
  }

  @keyframes fadeIn {
    from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(-20px); filter: blur(4px); }
    to { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); filter: blur(0); }
  }

  /* Remove default arrows in Firefox */
  summary {
    list-style: none;
  }
</style>